ng, Yung, Bin, Cao, Huang, Jing, Wen, Zhen, Biao, Chang, Chi, Quan, Yaping.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 倪, meaning ‘boundary’ or ‘infants’ in ancient Chinese: adopted in order to escape from a feud in place of the Chinese surname 郳, which is also pronounced Ni. The original surname was from Ni (郳), the name of an ancient state, also called Little Zhu (located in Shandong province), granted to the son of Duke Wu of Zhu (ruler of the state of Zhu, died 796  BC ). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), the name of the state was adopted as a surname.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 賴, see   Lai   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Lai","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Ching, Kwok, Ming, Wing, Wai, Wen, Chi, Chun, Ho, Kam, Man, Yee.  Vietnamese Hung, Thanh, Tuan, Hoa, Ky, Lan, Thang, Tien, Trang, Tu, Yen, Anh.","Chinese: Mandarin or Cantonese form of the surname 賴, meaning ‘depend on’ in Chinese: from Lai (賴), the name of a state (located in Henan province), which was annexed by the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 來, meaning ‘to come’ in Chinese: (i) simplified form of the placename Lai (郲), the name of a fief (located in Henan province) during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). (ii) adopted in place of the Chinese surname Lai (萊) which originated from the name of a fief/state. After its annihilation by the state of Qi, people simplified the name as 萊 in order to escape from political persecutions."]},{"name":"Ny","meanings":["Swedish: ornamental or soldier's name from <i>ny</i> ‘new’. It may sometimes derive from a placename beginning with <i>Ny-</i>.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 倪 (see   Ni  ) or 聶 (see   Nie   2)."]}]},{"name":"Úna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Irish Úna . In Irish legend Úna is the mother of the hero Conn Cétchathach (Conn of the Hundred Battles). It was also the name of the beloved of the 17th-century poet  Tomás Láidir Costello : banned by her parents from seeing him, Úna fell into a decline and died, leaving him to mourn her in his verse. The Anglicized form of the name is sometimes taken to be from the feminine of Latin <i>unus</i> ‘one’. It is the name used by Spenser for the lady of the Red Cross Knight in The Faerie Queene: he probably had Latin rather than Irish in mind, even though he worked in Ireland for a while. The Irish name has also been Anglicized as   Unity  ,   Juno  ,   Winifred  , and   Agnes ."],"variants":[{"name":"Euna","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Ùna ."]},{"name":"Oona","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Úna ."]},{"name":"Una","meanings":["Anglicized form of Irish Úna . In Irish legend Úna is the mother of the hero Conn Cétchathach (Conn of the Hundred Battles). It was also the name of the beloved of the 17th-century poet  Tomás Láidir Costello : banned by her parents from seeing him, Úna fell into a decline and died, leaving him to mourn her in his verse. The Anglicized form of the name is sometimes taken to be from the feminine of Latin <i>unus</i> ‘one’. It is the name used by Spenser for the lady of the Red Cross Knight in The Faerie Queene: he probably had Latin rather than Irish in mind, even though he worked in Ireland for a while. The Irish name has also been Anglicized as   Unity  ,   Juno  ,   Winifred  , and   Agnes ."]},{"name":"Oonagh","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Úna ."]},{"name":"Juno","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Irish name Úna , assimilated to the name of the Roman goddess <i>Juno</i>, consort of Jupiter."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Úna Ní Conchubhair, Queen of Thomond was born about 1330, in Ulster, Ireland as the daughter of O'Conner Core and Mrs O'Conner Core. She married Mathghamhain Maonmhaighe Ó Briain King of Thomond in 1350, in Ennis, County Clare, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in Ennis, County Clare, Ireland, and was buried in Ennis 1, Ennis, County Clare, Ireland."},"et":{"about 1330–about 1390":"umbes 1330–umbes 1390","1330–1390":"1330–1390","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1355–1400":"1355–1400","1360–1426":"1360–1426","1382–1498":"1382–1498","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","about 1360":"umbes 1360","about 1382":"umbes 1382","about 1390":"umbes 1390","before 1330":"enne 1330","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1390":"1390","1426":"1426","1315":"1315","Abt 1355":"umbes 1355","1400":"1400","1498":"1498","1355":"1355","about 1330":"umbes 1330","Corcumruadh, Donegal, Ulster, Ireland":"Ulster, Iirimaa","Ennis, Clare, Munster, Ireland":"Ennis, County Clare, Iirimaa","Kingdom of Thomond, Ireland":"Kingdom of Thomond, Iirimaa","Diocese of Limerick, Munster, Ireland":"Diocese of Limerick, Munster, Iirimaa","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Ennis Friary, Ennis, Clare, Munster, Ireland":"Ennis 1, Ennis, County Clare, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"about 1330–about 1390":"noin 1330–noin 1390","1330–1390":"1330–1390","1315–Male":"1315–Kuollut","1355–1400":"1355–1400","1360–1426":"1360–1426","1382–1498":"1382–1498","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","about 1360":"noin 1360","about 1382":"noin 1382","about 1390":"noin 1390","before 1330":"ennen vuotta 1330","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1390":"1390","1426":"1426","1315":"1315","Abt 1355":"noin 1355","1400":"1400","1498":"1498","1355":"1355","about 1330":"noin 1330","Corcumruadh, Donegal, Ulster, Ireland":"Ulster, Irlanti","Ennis, Clare, Munster, Ireland":"Ennis, County Clare, Irlanti","Kingdom of Thomond, Ireland":"Kingdom of Thomond, Irlanti","Diocese of Limerick, Munster, Ireland":"Diocese of Limerick, Munster, Irlanti","Ireland":"Irlanti","Ennis Friary, Ennis, Clare, Munster, Ireland":"Ennis 1, Ennis, County Clare, Irlanti"},"fr":{"about 1330–about 1390":"environ 1330–environ 1390","1330–1390":"1330–1390","1315–Male":"1315–Décédé